Cook,<br><br>
I sent you a private email on Sunday offering you the &quot;truth&quot; you are searching for. Truth that was not clouded by what you term &quot;communist propaganda&quot;. The reason I wished to converse with you back channel was because I am not interested in implicating anyone in an open channel forum.<br><br>
You never responded.<br><br>
My interest is truth also. I was there and have actual experiences on which I base my opinions. These experiences are not fiction or hearsay. They are not a result of my being &quot;duped&quot; by people such as Jane Fonda. <br><br>
I have never maintained that the majority of combat forces were guilty of wanton acts. However, based on my individual experience, nothing I hear from other Vietnam vets comes to me as a shock. <br><br>
In the Vietnam Protest thread I mentioned an incident that occurred at LZ Bayonet where unarmed Vietnamese farmers were shot at. They were out 5 minutes past curfew. You stated that you would have fired over their heads. Then, if they didn't &quot;di di&quot;, &quot;you would not hesitate to open up.&quot; After the first shots were fired at these peasants - they were desperately trying to herd their cattle away from the fire that was continuing despite their effort to flee.<br><br>
If I told you that, to the best of my recollection, Bayonet had not been hit by a ground assault in 1970 would you really have done that? I was at Bayonet infrequently, as our Brigade was turning it over to the ARVNs. However, I can state that it was in a relatively secure area, near Chu Lai.<br><br>
The men were farmers moving away from us - on their way home - and it was 5 minutes after curfew. The men who were shooting at them were wrong to do so.<br><br>
If the war had a positive effect on you, I am glad for you. If only a minimum of the men you served with have experienced the effects of PTSD, that is something to be truly grateful about.<br><br>
Many suffer from PTSD, though. I am positive that those who testified at the Winter Soldier's Investigation suffer from it, as do the ones I described at LZ Bayonet.<br><br>
To be sure, NOT all who suffer from PTSD are guilty of anything like I have described.<br><br>
You like to write about your experiences in Vietnam. Fine by me. But, your stature or the weight of your stories do not increase in direct proportion to your condemnations and name calling of people who protested the type of act I described as taking place at LZ Bayonet.<br><br>

